## Promising “Peaks” from Standard Physics Experiments

The energy crystal substrate φ is difficult to isolate directly, but many mainstream experiments inadvertently expose its properties. Here are some of the most promising examples where SRC reinterprets results through this lens.

### Direct Wigner Crystal Imaging 
- **Experiment:** Direct imaging of electrons forming perfect triangular lattice in 2D systems
- **Year/Status:** 2024–2025 (published) by Princeton, Berkeley groups  
- **Observed Anomalies:**
    - Softer crystals than expected from pure Coulomb repulsion
    - Heavier effective mass in certain regimes 
    - Anomalous Hall effects linked to Berry curvature
    - Transitions driven by frequency-dependent effects
- **SRC Reinterpretation:** Direct visualization of the energy crystal's ordered lattice state

### RHIC Spin Correlation  
- **Experiment:** High-energy quark-antiquark spin alignment from vacuum fluctuations 
- **Year/Status:** Feb 2026 (published) in Nature  
- **Observed Anomalies:**
    - Quark and antiquark pairs emerging from "nothing"
- **SRC Reinterpretation:** Spalling of defects from the energy crystal substrate; virtual excitations becoming real

### Dynamical Casimir Effect & Four-Wave Mixing
- **Experiment:** Photons generated by oscillating boundaries in vacuum 
- **Year/Status:** 2025 (Oxford/Lisbon simulations + experiments)  
- **Observed Anomalies:**
    - Shear-mode excitations triggered by rapid perturbations of the substrate

### Analog Gravity / Superfluids
- **Experiment:** Sonic black holes and Hawking-like radiation in fluids  
- **Year/Status:** Ongoing research (2000s–2026) by Unruh, Steinhauer, Weinfurtner et al. 
- **Observed Anomalies:**
    - Fluid analogs of refractive gradients and horizon cutoffs

### Casimir Force Measurements
- **Experiment:** High-precision measurements on quantum vacuum fluctuations  
- **Year/Status:** Ongoing (2020s)  
- **Observed Anomalies:**
    - Background "breathing" or zero-point shear modes in the crystal 

### Event Horizon Telescope Polarization & Jets
- **Experiment:** Unexpected polarization twists near black hole horizons
- **Year/Status:** 2024–2026 EHT data
- **Observed Anomalies:**
    - Refractive cutoff boundaries at extreme high-ρ(φ) pinches

